metadata.name: Rough Cuts #493
metadata.description:
Abstract generative artwork that explores composition and form by cutting canvas with straight lines. Coded brushwork gives a real-painting look to each piece.

Options:

- press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to save hi-res PNG images

Created using p5js.

metadata.name: Pixel Spaceships #256
metadata.description:
"Pixel Spaceships" is retro pixel pop art.  Spaceship-like forms are algorithmically generated by the hundreds, even thousands!  It is an exploration of generative algorithms, an examination of limited perception and the power of suggestion, and intended to evoke a nostalgia for the artistic sensibilities imposed by the hardware limitations of early arcade machines.

Further write-up:  https://www.davebollinger.us/pixelspaceships

Presented in a form suitable for large-format print if desired.  Each minting provides up to 100 retries via parameters to help obtain a preferred style.  (Though note that some features are quite rare, so a bit of luck may still be involved.)  Exploration is encouraged!

CONTROLS:

Press 's' to save the image.

Press a number key to adjust internal resolution (do this prior to saving):
  '1' : 1200px x  1800px ( 4" x  6" @300dpi) (default)
  '2' : 2400px x  3600px ( 8" x 12" @300dpi)
  '3' : 3600px x  5400px (12" x 18" @300dpi)
  '4' : 4800px x  7200px (16" x 24" @300dpi)
  '5' : 6000px x  9000px (20" x 30" @300dpi)
  '6' : 7200px x 10800px (24" x 36" @300dpi)

Note that changing the resolution will force the image to regenerate.  Regeneration at higher resolutions may take longer, particularly for complex scenes and/or rare features.

metadata.name: Adjacent #116
metadata.description:
Adjacent is the third in a set of collections based on a month-long study of Edward Zajec, one of the early pioneers of generative art. This piece focuses on the study of Diagonal White, a series he developed between 1970 and 1975.

In 1976, Ruth Leavitt published a collection of papers titled "Artist & Computer", which highlighted the 35 prominent generative artists and asked them to discuss their work. They were posed questions like, "Do you feel art work created with a computer has now or will have an impact on art as a whole in the future?". Edward Zajec was a subject of one of those papers and in it detailed the approach to Diagonal White. 

The original program was run on a CDC 6200 computer at The Univeresiry of Trieste. The programming was done in collaboration with Dr. Matjaz Hmeljak, his long-time technical partner. Inspired by his collaborative relationship, Adjacent the output of a partnership between Christine Hall and Chris Maddern.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save a high-resolution version of the image

Made in p5js
Created January 2023
By @christine_hall and @chrismaddern

metadata.name: Sketch Block #25
metadata.description:
At the heart of "Sketch Block" is the concept of the sketch block itself - a blank canvas where the possibilities for creation are endless. The name "Sketch Block" reflects the process of creation that inspired the token's design. Like an artist's sketchbook, the token captures the playful experimentation and exploration that underlies the creative process.

The hand-drawn style gives a playful feel to the project, with each shape looking as if it was quickly drawn onto the canvas. Along with the use of vibrant color palettes with tones ranging from soft pastels to bold and bright tones, the projects can produce a wide range of different results.


----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

User Controls:

- Press 'h' to save the image

metadata.name: The Arcade State #49
metadata.description:
"The Arcade State is a strange place.
You can only walk in four directions. Which will it be? 
As you make your way across the landscape, you will discover lush grasslands, grim structures, and colorful grounds. And if you get lucky, you might unearth artifacts of other times, hidden deep inside the system."
   - The Architect -


I am an artist and a scientist fueled by challenges. I'm most creative when I can't work under perfect conditions and I have to improvise to find a solution.
For The Arcade State, I constrained myself to only using four angles along the circle (45, 90, 135, and 180 degrees) while still producing interesting images with depth and variety.


Keys:
Press 'e' to export the image in HD  (1600x2000)
Press 'h' to export the image in UHD (4800x6000) - this will take a few seconds

metadata.name: The Golden Hour #75
metadata.description:
"The Golden Hour," is my generative art project that attempts to blur the lines between generative art and photography. Inspired by the magical moments of twilight, dusk and dawn.

The Golden Hour is a fleeting yet magical window just after sunrise and just before sunset, offering a palette of warm, soft light that transforms the ordinary into the extraordinary. This project aims to evoke that same sense of wonder.

On a small screen or mobile device, I want viewers to question whether they are looking at a photograph of a landscape. Upon closer inspection, it becomes clear that these are generative artworks, not photographs. Of course, with the number of mints available, I have had to introduce more randomness, so I know that some will not necessarily give that impression if they have a bright magenta sky. This element of unpredictability ensures that every piece is distinct, offering a fresh perspective on the interplay between code, art and nature.

------------------------------------------------
Press s to save the image.
Press e for endless animation.
Press p to pause animation.
------------------------------------------------

To save at a higher resolution, open the live view of your token, add &scale=3 or &scale=4 to the end of the URL. Be mindful that larger outputs will take longer to render. The default scale is 2.

I used the p5js JavaScript library to create this collection and minify-js to minimise the files.
